reasoning: 1. Circle of Competence: Google is a complex tech conglomerate—search algorithms, ad auctions, cloud services and AI—that falls outside my straightforward consumer-oriented circle of competence. As I’ve said, ‘Risk comes from not knowing what you’re doing.’ 2. Moat: On paper there’s a network effect in search and advertising scale, but in fast-moving tech, today’s advantage can erode tomorrow. 3. Management: Alphabet’s team under Sundar Pichai seems capable and shareholder-friendly, but they’re dabbling in a host of moonshots with unclear paybacks. 4. Financial Health: While Alphabet historically has had a fortress balance sheet and ample cash flow, the analysis here admits ‘insufficient data’ to confirm consistency. 5. Valuation: With no reliable intrinsic value estimate or margin of safety, we can’t determine if today’s price represents a bargain or a premium. 6. Long-Term Prospects: AI and cloud may drive growth, yet fierce competition and regulatory scrutiny introduce sizable uncertainty. 7. Comparison: I’d rather deploy capital into businesses I thoroughly understand—Coca-Cola, Apple as a consumer play, BNSF—where durable moats and predictable earnings meet my criteria. In short, I’ll sit this one out until clarity and valuation fall into my comfort zone.
